spanning the 6 external degrees of freedom. For a molecule with N atoms and Cartesian coordinates
x = (x1, y1, z1, . . . , xN, yN, zN)T ∈R3N, the six basis vectors correspond to three translations and three
infinitesimal rotations. The unnormalized translation vectors are: tx = (1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, . . . , 1, 0, 0)T , (C.1)
ty = (0, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0, . . . , 0, 1, 0)T , (C.2)
tz = (0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 1, . . . , 0, 0, 1)T . (C.3) The unnormalized infinitesimal rotation vectors (about the molecular center of mass r0) are: rx = (0, z1 −z0, −(y1 −y0), . . . , 0, zN −z0, −(yN −y0))T , (C.4)
ry = (−(z1 −z0), 0, x1 −x0, . . . , −(zN −z0), 0, xN −x0)T , (C.5)
rz = (y1 −y0, −(x1 −x0), 0, . . . , yN −y0, −(xN −x0), 0)T . (C.6) where (xi, yi, zi) are the coordinates of atom i, and (x0, y0, z0) is the center of mass.
